	<!-- <h2></h2> -->
			<div class="longform post_img fullwidth">
			<img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/secondhalf2024-copy.jpg" alt="" class="entry_post"/>
		</div>
				<h1>Lit Hub&#8217;s Most Anticipated Books of 2024, Part Two</h1>
		<h2>192 Books to Read in the Second Half of the Year</h2>
    <div class="inner">
		<div class="post_header_wrapper">
    				</div>
				<div class="author_info" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
			<div class="author_name">By&nbsp;<a href="https://lithub.com/author/emily-temple/" itemprop="url"><span itemprop="name">Emily&nbsp;Temple</span></a></div>
			<div class="author_hr"><hr/></div>
			<div class="publish_date">July 10, 2024</div>
		</div>
		<div class="social_links">
						<a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?via=lithub&text=Lit+Hub%27s+Most+Anticipated+Books+of+2024%2C+Part+Two&url=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2Flit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two%2F"><span class="social_twitter"></span></a>
			<a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2Flit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two%2F&t=Lit+Hub%27s+Most+Anticipated+Books+of+2024%2C+Part+Two"><span class="social_facebook"></span></a>
					</div>
    <div class="inner">
    	<!-- Begin main content -->
    	<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
    			
										<!-- Begin each blog post -->
						<div class="post_wrapper" style="padding-top:0;">
							<div class="post_inner_wrapper">
						    	<div class="post_wrapper_inner">
										<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
								        
										<p>Well, it&#8217;s been a pretty bad year so far, all things considered, with the strong potential to get worse. But as always, there&#8217;s a silver lining (of sorts): the books. Now that <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">the year&#8217;s reading is half over</a>, it&#8217;s time for an updated preview, so here are the books the Literary Hub staff is most looking forward to reading in the back half of 2024.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues below</span><script id="9b7a21a47fb44523b011db6d4f4cad23">(new Image()).src = 'https://capi.connatix.com/tr/si?token=546998bb-b9c0-4480-8c91-3e307220efff&cid=86b7c382-5e20-4129-84db-dea768f4d688';  cnx.cmd.push(function() {    cnx({      playerId: "546998bb-b9c0-4480-8c91-3e307220efff"    }).render("9b7a21a47fb44523b011db6d4f4cad23");  });</script></div>
<h1 style="text-align: center;">July</h1>
<h4><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231502" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/51o8iwwyiel-_sl1200_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/51o8iwWYieL._SL1200_.jpg" data-orig-size="774,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Joy Williams, Concerning the Future of Souls" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/51o8iwWYieL._SL1200_-194x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/51o8iwWYieL._SL1200_-660x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231502 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/51o8iwWYieL._SL1200_-194x300.jpg" alt="Joy Williams, Concerning the Future of Souls" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/51o8iwWYieL._SL1200_-194x300.jpg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/51o8iwWYieL._SL1200_-660x1024.jpg 660w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/51o8iwWYieL._SL1200_-768x1191.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/51o8iwWYieL._SL1200_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/51o8iwWYieL._SL1200_-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/51o8iwWYieL._SL1200_.jpg 774w" sizes="(max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></h4>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Joy Williams, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781959030591" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Concerning the Future of Souls</a><br />
</em>Tin House, July 2</strong></h5>
<p>I was completely enthralled by the excerpt from this collection of short pieces that ran in the Spring<em> Paris Review</em>. The complete <em>Concerning the Future of Souls</em> contains 99 pieces about death, most of them following Azrael—the devoted angel that escorts souls to their judgment at God’s feet—and Satan, who spars with Azrael. Jung, Nietzsche, and Rilke appear, as do horses, butterflies, and tortoises, all united in the shared experience of mortality. Each piece is small, its own shining gem set into constellations with its neighbors. Williams is a beautiful and intelligent writer, and her short meditations are poetic, sad, and often quite funny too.  <em>–James Folta, contributing writer</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="238906" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/attachment/9780063319974/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/9780063319974.jpg" data-orig-size="659,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="evenings and weekends" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/9780063319974-198x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/9780063319974.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-238906 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/9780063319974-198x300.jpg" alt="evenings and weekends" width="198" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/9780063319974-198x300.jpg 198w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/9780063319974-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/9780063319974-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/9780063319974.jpg 659w" sizes="(max-width: 198px) 100vw, 198px" /></p>
<h5 style="text-align: right;"><strong>Oisín McKenna, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063319974" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Evenings and Weekends</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Mariner, July 2</strong></h5>
<p>Irish spoken-word artist and playwright Oisín (pronounced “ush-een,” in case you’re curious) McKenna’s debut novel is a queer, multi-generational, polyphonic story set in London during a sweltering June weekend in 2019. It’s being billed as “Sally Rooney meets Torrey Peters,” which sounds pretty incredible, and just received <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/article/2024/may/08/evenings-and-weekends-by-oisin-mckenna-review-a-love-letter-to-london-under-pressure" class="external" target="_blank">this rave review</a> in the <em>Guardian</em>: “For even as it utters a howl of rage at broken, late-capitalist Britain, <em>Evenings and Weekends</em> is a love letter to the city—the chance it offers to forge your own identity, and the interconnectedness of urban life.” <em>–Dan Sheehan, Book Marks Editor in Chief</em></p>
<h5><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231490" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/81pnw3ra40l-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81PNW3RA40L._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="994,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Liz Moore, The God of the Woods" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81PNW3RA40L._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81PNW3RA40L._SL1500_-679x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231490 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81PNW3RA40L._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" alt="Liz Moore, The God of the Woods" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81PNW3RA40L._SL1500_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81PNW3RA40L._SL1500_-679x1024.jpg 679w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81PNW3RA40L._SL1500_-768x1159.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81PNW3RA40L._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81PNW3RA40L._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81PNW3RA40L._SL1500_.jpg 994w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Liz Moore, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593418918" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The God of the Woods</em></a><br />
</strong><strong>Riverhead, July 2</strong></h5>
<p>Liz Moore&#8217;s <em>Long Bright River</em> was a spectacular pivot to crime for Liz Moore and her new one should cement her reputation. It&#8217;s a great summer read about missing children at a summer camp, with a tinge of &#8220;all of this has happened before&#8221; looming around the edges. Reading this felt like discovering Tana French&#8217;s <em>In the Woods</em>—and not just because of the &#8220;child disappeared in the woods&#8221; angle, but because it&#8217;s unputdownable and thrillingly constructed. <em>–Drew Broussard, Podcasts Editor</em></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues below</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231504" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/pink-slime-9781668049778_xlg/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/pink-slime-9781668049778_xlg.jpg" data-orig-size="643,900" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Fernanda Trias, trans. Heather Cleary, Pink Slime" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/pink-slime-9781668049778_xlg-214x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/pink-slime-9781668049778_xlg.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231504 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/pink-slime-9781668049778_xlg-214x300.jpg" alt="Fernanda Trias, trans. Heather Cleary, Pink Slime" width="214" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/pink-slime-9781668049778_xlg-214x300.jpg 214w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/pink-slime-9781668049778_xlg-43x60.jpg 43w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/pink-slime-9781668049778_xlg-36x50.jpg 36w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/pink-slime-9781668049778_xlg.jpg 643w" sizes="(max-width: 214px) 100vw, 214px" /></h5>
<h5 class="Body" style="text-align: right;"><strong>Fernanda Trias, tr. Heather Cleary, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668049778" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Pink Slime</a><br />
</em>Scribner, July 2</strong></h5>
<p class="Body"><a href="https://lithub.com/18-new-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As previously recommended:</em></a> I have been waiting for this book since last summer’s <span class="Hyperlink0"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/10/books/latin-american-science-fiction.html" class="external" target="_blank"><i>Times</i> write-up</a> </span>of the new wave of speculative fiction coming out of Latin America, and it doesn’t disappoint. This novel is being comped to the works of Samanta Schweblin and Mariana Enriquez—and while those are useful comparisons, particularly in the case of Schweblin’s <em>Fever Dream</em>—<em>Pink Slime</em> is very much its own beast, due to become a frequent comp title in its own right.</p>
<p class="Body">It’s set in a moment of ecological anxiety where a red algae bloom has created a ‘red wind’ off the sea that infects and kills most of the people exposed to it, where healthy/natural food is increasingly hard to come by and people eat processed meat paste instead. The narrator is struggling to adapt to this new world, trying her best to serve as a nanny for a constantly hungry boy and to take care of her stubborn mother and her dying ex-husband. Trías’s prose, in Heather Cleary’s terrific translation, pulls you in slowly until you find you can’t put the book down—like being locked in during a wind alarm, trying your best to keep your footing. I’ve already ordered Trías’s earlier novel <i>The Rooftop</i> from her UK publisher, because I’m that excited to read more. <em>–DB</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="238907" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/michael-castleman-the-untold-story-of-books/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Michael-Castleman-The-Untold-Story-of-Books.jpeg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Michael Castleman, The Untold Story of Books" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Michael-Castleman-The-Untold-Story-of-Books-200x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Michael-Castleman-The-Untold-Story-of-Books.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-238907 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Michael-Castleman-The-Untold-Story-of-Books-200x300.jpeg" alt="Michael Castleman, The Untold Story of Books" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Michael-Castleman-The-Untold-Story-of-Books-200x300.jpeg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Michael-Castleman-The-Untold-Story-of-Books-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Michael-Castleman-The-Untold-Story-of-Books-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Michael-Castleman-The-Untold-Story-of-Books.jpeg 667w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Michael Castleman, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781961884083" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Untold Story of Books</a><br />
</em>Unnamed Press, July 2</strong></h5>
<p style="text-align: left;">Here’s one that’s perfect for Lit Hub readers: Michael Castleman’s history of the book business takes a long view of the 600-year-old industry that produces and distributes the art we love. He divides his history of publishing into three distinct business models, each one overtaking and replacing the last: the post-Gutenberg era that led to the first mass-produced books; the 19th-century machine age with higher costs and more contracts; and the third and current age of tech disruption, wholesaling, and a return to self-publishing. Castleman’s history is approachable, and he deftly explains the macro of technological innovations and economic incentives, as well as the micro, with lots of fun tidbits and tangents. <em>–JF</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="238908" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/emily-dunlay-teddy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Emily-Dunlay-Teddy-.jpeg" data-orig-size="663,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Emily Dunlay, Teddy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Emily-Dunlay-Teddy--199x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Emily-Dunlay-Teddy-.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-238908 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Emily-Dunlay-Teddy--199x300.jpeg" alt="" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Emily-Dunlay-Teddy--199x300.jpeg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Emily-Dunlay-Teddy--40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Emily-Dunlay-Teddy--33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Emily-Dunlay-Teddy-.jpeg 663w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: right;"><strong>Emily Dunlay, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063354890" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Teddy</em></a><br />
Harper, July 2</strong></h5>
<p>In this madcap tale of espionage and adventure, a Dallas debutante marries a foreign service worker and heads to mid-1960s Italy, determined to put her wild days behind her and finally Behave. Events conspire to foil her goals of proper deportment, and soon enough, she’s involved in a blackmail scheme, embassy hijinks, and the most daunting task of all: finding a couture dress that can fit her without needing to be tailored. <em>Teddy</em> is not just a fabulous historical novel—it’s a manifesto against the patriarchy, and a liberating experience of watching a woman free herself. <em>–Molly Odintz, CrimeReads Managing Editor</em></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues below</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231503" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/81a6nb4jg6l-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81A6nB4jG6L._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="993,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Lauren Aliza Green, The World After Alice" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81A6nB4jG6L._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81A6nB4jG6L._SL1500_-678x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231503 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81A6nB4jG6L._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" alt="Lauren Aliza Green, The World After Alice" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81A6nB4jG6L._SL1500_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81A6nB4jG6L._SL1500_-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81A6nB4jG6L._SL1500_-768x1160.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81A6nB4jG6L._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81A6nB4jG6L._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81A6nB4jG6L._SL1500_.jpg 993w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Lauren Aliza Green, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593654132" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The World After Alice</em></a><br />
Viking, July 2</strong></h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As previously recommended:</em></a> Lauren Green is a poet and a debut author (of <em>Forbes</em> 30 Under 30 fame) with a much-heralded title coming this July. <em>The World After Alice </em>is about the death of a girl named Alice and a wedding that takes place twelve years later. Alice’s brother, Benji, is marrying her best friend, Morgan, and the families must come together and confront their rocky and devastating past while attempting to celebrate and seek joy in the union. With betrayals and grief and secrets all threatening to interrupt the wedding weekend, <em>The World After Alice </em>is a juicy and emotional read that surprises as much as it entertains. –<em>Julia Hass, contributing editor</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="239291" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/9781250904294-2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/9781250904294-1.jpg" data-orig-size="323,500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="9781250904294" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/9781250904294-1-194x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/9781250904294-1.jpg" class="wp-image-239291 size-medium alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/9781250904294-1-194x300.jpg" alt="" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/9781250904294-1-194x300.jpg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/9781250904294-1-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/9781250904294-1-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/9781250904294-1.jpg 323w" sizes="(max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></p>
<h5 style="text-align: right;"><strong>O.O Sangoyomi, <a href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250904294" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Masquerade</em></a><br />
Forge Books, July 2</strong></h5>
<p>Sangoyomi&#8217;s debut took me by wondrous surprise: I read this book in under 24 hours. Loosely riffing on the Persephone myth but set in pre-colonial Saharan Africa, it&#8217;s the story of a woman plucked from the edges of society (a single woman, working as a blacksmith: must be a witch!) to suddenly marry a warrior king. Perfectly plotted and featuring a main character worth dying for, <em>Masquerade </em>is a must-read for anybody who enjoys pre-colonial narratives, historical fiction, palace intrigue, epic romance. It&#8217;s an absolute stunner. —<em>DB</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="237670" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/18-new-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/816csaljbtl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/816csalJbtL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="978,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="state of paradise laura van den berg" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/816csalJbtL._SL1500_-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/816csalJbtL._SL1500_-668x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-237670 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/816csalJbtL._SL1500_-196x300.jpg" alt="state of paradise laura van den berg" width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/816csalJbtL._SL1500_-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/816csalJbtL._SL1500_-668x1024.jpg 668w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/816csalJbtL._SL1500_-768x1178.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/816csalJbtL._SL1500_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/816csalJbtL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/816csalJbtL._SL1500_.jpg 978w" sizes="(max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Laura van den Berg, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374612207" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>State of Paradise</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>FSG, July 9</strong></h5>
<p style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="https://lithub.com/18-new-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As previously recommended:</em></a> As I’m sure I’ve mentioned on this website before, I will go wherever Laura van den Berg and her eerie, uncanny imagination lead, even to the much-maligned sunshine state in storm season. <em>State of Paradise</em>, van den Berg’s third novel, is the story of a creatively unfulfilled ghost writer who returns—with her running-obsessed husband in tow—to the town where she grew up (and where she was briefly institutionalized a couple of decades previous).</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">There, in a post-pandemic central Florida, as the summer heat rises and her literary taskmasters&#8217; demands become more opaque, very odd things begin to happen. Storms rage, people vanish, irises change color, snails gather en masse, and a virtual world called Mind’s Eye begins to supplant the real. But then, how can the narrator or her unravelling sister be certain that their reality is, well, <em>real</em>? And what knowledge is the famous thriller  novelist who signs our protagonist&#8217;s paychecks hiding in his Floridian manse? A wry, surreal, lushly atmospheric metafictional mystery, I fell under the swampy spell of this novel from the get-go. <em>–DS</em></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues below</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231506" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/6120i5cbzl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/6120I5cBzL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="992,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Yasmin Zaher, The Coin" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/6120I5cBzL._SL1500_-198x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/6120I5cBzL._SL1500_-677x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231506 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/6120I5cBzL._SL1500_-198x300.jpg" alt="Yasmin Zaher, The Coin" width="198" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/6120I5cBzL._SL1500_-198x300.jpg 198w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/6120I5cBzL._SL1500_-677x1024.jpg 677w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/6120I5cBzL._SL1500_-768x1161.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/6120I5cBzL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/6120I5cBzL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/6120I5cBzL._SL1500_.jpg 992w" sizes="(max-width: 198px) 100vw, 198px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: right;"><strong>Yasmin Zaher, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781646222100" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Coin</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Catapult, July 9</strong></h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/18-new-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As previously recommended:</em></a> Yasmin Zaher’s <em>The Coin</em><em> </em>is a novel of big ideas hiding in chic little packages—packages not unlike the Birkin bags that feature so heavily in the plot. In slick, clever chapters, we follow an unnamed Millennial woman around (initially) New York City. But if you feel you’ve heard this one before, you’d be wrong.</p>
<p>Our hero’s POV proves conspicuously strange, and her adventures surreal. A wealthy Palestinian—new in town, but recently orphaned—our narrator’s primed to observe the contradictions attending daily life in America. But as she fails to square those contradictions (poverty next to wealth, dirt next to beauty), she begins to disintegrate. Her vanity morphs into a cleanliness obsession. Her do-gooding instincts, sprouted in the soil of the “underprivileged boys” school where she teaches, go South. And the tragedy she’s been running from—which is, I think, a synecdoche for a global one—becomes impossible to avoid.</p>
<p>This is a sneakily profound book about material excess, the cost of ease, and all the broken promises an empire is built on. Yet it’s fun, even merry! The frosted-but-confident voice reminded me of Isa Epley, from Marlowe Granados’ <em>Happy Hour</em>. (“I’ve always been motivated by pleasure, never by money,” our narrator confides on the first page.) And Zaher’s relentless eye for modern details made me think of Halle Butler’s <em>The New Me. –Brittany Allen, contributing writer</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231507" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/71kyhred1xl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71kyHrEd1xL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1008,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Kevin Barry, The Heart in Winter" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71kyHrEd1xL._SL1500_-202x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71kyHrEd1xL._SL1500_-688x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231507 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71kyHrEd1xL._SL1500_-202x300.jpg" alt="Kevin Barry, The Heart in Winter" width="202" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71kyHrEd1xL._SL1500_-202x300.jpg 202w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71kyHrEd1xL._SL1500_-688x1024.jpg 688w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71kyHrEd1xL._SL1500_-768x1143.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71kyHrEd1xL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71kyHrEd1xL._SL1500_-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71kyHrEd1xL._SL1500_.jpg 1008w" sizes="(max-width: 202px) 100vw, 202px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Kevin Barry, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780385550598" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Heart in Winter</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Doubleday, July 9</strong></h5>
<p style="font-weight: 400;"><a href="https://lithub.com/18-new-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As previously recommended:</em></a> All the blurb that should be required for you to saddle up your horse and ride hard toward your nearest bookstore on July 9 is this: Kevin Barry does <em>Deadwood</em>. Barry’s signature linguistic brio is on full, glorious display in this rollicking tale of a young(ish) Irish immigrant—a melancholic, opium-smoking balladeer and occasional Cyrano-for-hire named Tom Rourke—in a Montana mining town in 1891 who begins a passionate affair with Polly Gillespie, the fiery new bride of dull-as-ditchwater captain Long Anthony Harrington. The lovestruck duo rob a safe, steal a horse, and light out for the territory, with Harrington’s psychotic man Jago in hot pursuit. Barry never disappoints, but this one is a pure pleasure. A thrilling, tumescent, poetically vulgar, big-hearted romp of a novel, where the fearless blending of vernaculars makes for a wholly unique and utterly electrifying reading experience. <em>–DS</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="237499" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/18-new-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/91t7hfefxdl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91t7HFEfXDL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="971,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Chuck Tingle, Bury Your Gays" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91t7HFEfXDL._SL1500_-194x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91t7HFEfXDL._SL1500_-663x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-237499 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91t7HFEfXDL._SL1500_-194x300.jpg" alt="Chuck Tingle, Bury Your Gays" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91t7HFEfXDL._SL1500_-194x300.jpg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91t7HFEfXDL._SL1500_-663x1024.jpg 663w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91t7HFEfXDL._SL1500_-768x1186.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91t7HFEfXDL._SL1500_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91t7HFEfXDL._SL1500_-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91t7HFEfXDL._SL1500_.jpg 971w" sizes="(max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></h5>
<h5 class="Body" style="text-align: right;"><b>Chuck Tingle, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250874658" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><i>Bury Your Gays</i></a><br />
Tor Nightfire, July 9</b></h5>
<p class="Body"><a href="https://lithub.com/18-new-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As previously recommended:</em></a> I loved Chuck Tingle’s traditional-publishing debut <i>Camp Damascus </i>(a terrific possession/demonology novel that managed to both terrify and uplift) and<i> </i>his Tinglers remain an absolute delight, but I’m going to go out on a limb and say that <i>Bury Your Gays</i> is his best work yet. It deserves to be the literary equivalent of a massive summer blockbuster, and I’m using that term specifically because it is set in Hollywood and written by somebody who <i>gets it</i>: the suits are going to drive us all off the cliff of increasingly crappy AI-driven stories that have zero humanity to them whatsoever, but we-the-artists (and we-the-audiences) can and must push back!</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues below</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div>
<p class="Body">It also works as a total thrill-ride, following a screenwriter on the verge of his big moment (an Oscar nomination, critical and commercial success) only to discover that the suits want him to kill off the gay characters in his long-running series. When he declines, monsters from his horror movie days start appearing in real life and trying to kill him and his loved ones—coincidence? Outrageous publicity stunt? An over-the-top attempt to bring a rogue writer to heel? If you were on the picket lines last year, if original stories are important to you, if you too believe that love is real(!), then this one is for you—even if you don’t think you like horror, you’re gonna devour this. <em>–DB</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231508" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/519giwogpcl-_sl1200_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519giWOGpCL._SL1200_.jpg" data-orig-size="794,1200" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Emily Van Duyne, Loving Sylvia Plath" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519giWOGpCL._SL1200_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519giWOGpCL._SL1200_-678x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231508 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519giWOGpCL._SL1200_-199x300.jpg" alt="Emily Van Duyne, Loving Sylvia Plath" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519giWOGpCL._SL1200_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519giWOGpCL._SL1200_-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519giWOGpCL._SL1200_-768x1161.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519giWOGpCL._SL1200_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519giWOGpCL._SL1200_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/519giWOGpCL._SL1200_.jpg 794w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Emily Van Duyne, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781324006978" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Loving Sylvia Plath: A Reclamation</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>W.W. Norton, July 9</strong></h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As previously recommended:</em></a> A &#8220;radical&#8221; new reading of Plath&#8217;s life and legacy from Plath scholar, superfan, and <a href="https://lithub.com/author/emily-van-duyne/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Literary Hub contributor</a> Emily Van Duyne, which examines the many myths surrounding the poet before taking them apart, wiping off the grime, and reconstructing a new vision of Plath for the future. <em>–ET</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231509" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/71z6hvz6rl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71z6hvz6rL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="994,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Paolo Bacigalupi, Navola" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71z6hvz6rL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71z6hvz6rL._SL1500_-679x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231509 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71z6hvz6rL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" alt="Paolo Bacigalupi, Navola" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71z6hvz6rL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71z6hvz6rL._SL1500_-679x1024.jpg 679w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71z6hvz6rL._SL1500_-768x1159.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71z6hvz6rL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71z6hvz6rL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71z6hvz6rL._SL1500_.jpg 994w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: right;"><strong>Paolo Bacigalupi, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593535059" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Navola</em></a><br />
Knopf, July 9</strong></h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As previously recommended:</em></a> Paolo came up in YA and is set to release a wide-ranging fantasy about the families living in Navola, a city-state with a mysterious history. It’s a coming-of-age for Davico di Regulai who “will be expected to take the reins of power from his father and demonstrate his mastery of the games of Navolese diplomacy: knowing who to trust and who to doubt, and how to read what lies hidden behind a smile.” –<em>Janet Manley, contributing writer</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231729" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/carriecarolyncoco_fc/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CarrieCarolynCoco_FC-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="1708,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="CarrieCarolynCoco_FC" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CarrieCarolynCoco_FC-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CarrieCarolynCoco_FC-683x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231729 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CarrieCarolynCoco_FC-200x300.jpg" alt="" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CarrieCarolynCoco_FC-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CarrieCarolynCoco_FC-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CarrieCarolynCoco_FC-768x1151.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CarrieCarolynCoco_FC-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CarrieCarolynCoco_FC-1025x1536.jpg 1025w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CarrieCarolynCoco_FC-1366x2048.jpg 1366w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CarrieCarolynCoco_FC-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CarrieCarolynCoco_FC-scaled.jpg 1708w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Sarah Gerard, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781638930464" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Carrie Carolyn Coco</em></a><br />
Zando, July 9</strong></h5>
<p>It’s hard to imagine how painful it must have been for Gerard (author of the essay collection <em>Sunshine State </em>and the novel <em>True Love</em>) to write this hybrid work of investigative journalism, grief memoir, and dissection of the true crime genre. <em>Carrie Caroyln Coco<strong> </strong></em>is the story of Carolyn Bush, a twenty-five-year-old poet who was stabbed to death in her New York City apartment by her roommate in 2016, and of Gerard’s six-year quest to understand her friend’s singular life and brutal death. <em>–DS</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231510" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/71awvg66qll-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71awvg66QlL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="993,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Aysegul Savas, The Anthropologists" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71awvg66QlL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71awvg66QlL._SL1500_-678x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231510 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71awvg66QlL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" alt="Aysegul Savas, The Anthropologists" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71awvg66QlL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71awvg66QlL._SL1500_-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71awvg66QlL._SL1500_-768x1160.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71awvg66QlL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71awvg66QlL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71awvg66QlL._SL1500_.jpg 993w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: right;"><strong>Ayşegül Savas, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781639733064" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Anthropologists</em></a><br />
Bloomsbury, July 9</strong></h5>
<p>A couple searches for an apartment in a city foreign to both of them, imagining their possible futures as they go to viewings and negotiate their new world. Savaş is a master of moments of subtle power, and this one promises to be a gorgeous portrait of a relationship, with all its tenderness and bewilderment. <em>–Jessie Gaynor, Senior Editor</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="238910" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/toward-eternity-anton-hur/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/toward-eternity-anton-hur.jpeg" data-orig-size="657,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="toward eternity anton hur" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/toward-eternity-anton-hur-197x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/toward-eternity-anton-hur.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-238910 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/toward-eternity-anton-hur-197x300.jpeg" alt="toward eternity anton hur" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/toward-eternity-anton-hur-197x300.jpeg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/toward-eternity-anton-hur-39x60.jpeg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/toward-eternity-anton-hur-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/toward-eternity-anton-hur.jpeg 657w" sizes="(max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Anton Hur, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063344488" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Toward Eternity</em></a><br />
HarperVia, July 9</strong></h5>
<p>It would appear that National Book Award finalist Anton Hur is not just a brilliant translator (In 2022 Hur was nominated <em>twice</em> for the International Booker Prize for his translations of Bora Chung’s <em>Cursed Bunny </em>and Sang Young Park’s <em>Love in the Big City</em>), but a brilliant fiction writer as well. His debut novel, <em>Toward Eternity</em>—an Emily Dickenson-inspired existential sci-fi tale of “love, robots, and poetry” which <em>Kirkus</em> recently called “an unfailing affirmation of the persistence of love and art, even in the face of oblivion” has drawn comparisons to Kazuo Ishiguro’s <em>Klara and the Sun</em>, Emily St. John Mandel’s <em>Sea of Tranquility</em>, and <em>Blade Runner</em>. Sign me up. <em>–DS</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="238911" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/the-history-of-sound-ben-shattuck/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/the-history-of-sound-ben-shattuck.jpeg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="the history of sound ben shattuck" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/the-history-of-sound-ben-shattuck-199x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/the-history-of-sound-ben-shattuck.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-238911 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/the-history-of-sound-ben-shattuck-199x300.jpeg" alt="the history of sound ben shattuck" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/the-history-of-sound-ben-shattuck-199x300.jpeg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/the-history-of-sound-ben-shattuck-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/the-history-of-sound-ben-shattuck-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/the-history-of-sound-ben-shattuck.jpeg 662w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: right;"><strong>Ben Shattuck, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593490389" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The History of Sound</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Viking, July 9</strong></h5>
<p>Twelve interwoven stories set in and around New England make up this debut collection by Ben Shattuck. Shattuck has created an unusual and inviting premise wherein each story has a companion piece: the sister story holds a previously untold reveal from the other, secrets and insights that keep the reader hooked and entranced. You may have heard of Shattuck’s collection, as the titular story has already been optioned for film rights: a queer love story between fan favorites, Paul Mescal and Josh O’Conner. This piece, “The History of Sound”, is a gentle, ruminative memory of a love long since past, a nostalgic remembrance of music and tenderness and finding solace in one another. It leads the collection with a jolt of emotion, and the ensuing pieces follow suit, taking the reader down a path of place and care and remembrances, transported and transfixed.  –<em>JH</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231505" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/81mxxda17pl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81mXxDA17PL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="994,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Mateo Askaripour, This Great Hemisphere" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81mXxDA17PL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81mXxDA17PL._SL1500_-679x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231505 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81mXxDA17PL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" alt="Mateo Askaripour, This Great Hemisphere" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81mXxDA17PL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81mXxDA17PL._SL1500_-679x1024.jpg 679w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81mXxDA17PL._SL1500_-768x1159.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81mXxDA17PL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81mXxDA17PL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81mXxDA17PL._SL1500_.jpg 994w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Mateo Askaripour, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593472347" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>This Great Hemisphere</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Dutton, July 9</strong></h5>
<p>For his sophomore novel, the author of <em>Black Buck </em>has brought us a big, juicy speculative epic—part thriller, part mystery, part adventure, part SF yarn, part social satire, part allegory of colonialism. &#8220;I can&#8217;t help but to think that the spirit of the great prophet Octavia Butler hovers over <i>This Great Hemisphere</i>,&#8221; says Robert Jones, Jr. And well, I go where Octavia goes. <em>–Emily Temple, Managing Editor</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="238912" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/quincas-borba-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/quincas-borba-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="669,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="quincas borba copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/quincas-borba-copy-201x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/quincas-borba-copy.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-238912 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/quincas-borba-copy-201x300.jpg" alt="quincas borba" width="201" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/quincas-borba-copy-201x300.jpg 201w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/quincas-borba-copy-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/quincas-borba-copy-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/quincas-borba-copy.jpg 669w" sizes="(max-width: 201px) 100vw, 201px" /></p>
<h5 style="text-align: right;"><strong>Joaquim Maria Machado de Assis, tr. Margaret Jull Coasta &amp; Robin Patterson, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781324090687" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Quincas Borba</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Liveright, July 9</strong></h5>
<p>A new translation of Machado de Assis, one of South America&#8217;s most celebrated (and wonderfully bizarre) writers is excellent news. Jull Costa and Patterson&#8217;s excellent translation of <i><a href="https://bookshop.org/p/books/posthumous-memoirs-of-bras-cubas-joaquim-maria-machado-de-assis/15242637/?aid=132" class="external" target="_blank">The Posthumous Memoirs of Brás Cubas</a> </i>was playful, extremely funny, and deeply weird, so I&#8217;m looking forward to picking up this satire of wealth and progress (or perhaps &#8220;progress&#8221;?) in nineteenth century Brazil.  <em>–JG</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="238913" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/the-long-run-stacey-derasmo/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/the-long-run-stacey-derasmo.jpeg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="the long run stacey d&#8217;erasmo" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/the-long-run-stacey-derasmo-200x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/the-long-run-stacey-derasmo.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-238913 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/the-long-run-stacey-derasmo-200x300.jpeg" alt="the long run stacey d'erasmo" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/the-long-run-stacey-derasmo-200x300.jpeg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/the-long-run-stacey-derasmo-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/the-long-run-stacey-derasmo-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/the-long-run-stacey-derasmo.jpeg 667w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Stacey D&#8217;Erasmo, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781644452929" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Long Run: A Creative Inquiry</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Graywolf, July 9</strong></h5>
<p>For those of you who are creatively inclined it is not difficult to recall a time—in college, in your early twenties, perhaps—when you felt boldly energized by the idea (and practice) of making art, the feeling that you’d find the purpose of your life. And then jobs happened, and life, and it became harder and harder to return to that feeling… Facing her own questions about art-making and aging, writer Stacey D’Erasmo interviewed some truly brilliant—and old—artists about what has kept them going: from Merce Cunningham to Samuel R. Delany to Steve Earle to Taniá Leon the answers are as surprising and delightful as they are consistently similar. –<em>Jonny Diamond, Editor in Chief</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231511" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/a1bbisdqzbl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1bbiSDQzbL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Jesse Katz, The Rent Collectors" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1bbiSDQzbL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1bbiSDQzbL._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231511 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1bbiSDQzbL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" alt="Jesse Katz, The Rent Collectors" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1bbiSDQzbL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1bbiSDQzbL._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1bbiSDQzbL._SL1500_-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1bbiSDQzbL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1bbiSDQzbL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/A1bbiSDQzbL._SL1500_.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: right;"><strong>Jesse Katz, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662601736" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Rent Collectors: Exploitation, Murder, and Redemption in Immigrant LA</em></a><br />
Astra House, July 16</strong></h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As previously recommended:</em></a> Teenaged wannabe gangster Giovanni botches a hit, instead killing a newborn child in Los Angeles, and is in turn dragged over the Mexican border to be killed. Only that goes wrong too, and Giovanni sets off to bring the gang to justice. This true story looks at what a death is worth and how a crime can be forgiven. –<em>JM</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231512" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/71ar7ww01hl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71Ar7WW01HL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="993,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Halle Butler, Banal Nightmare" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71Ar7WW01HL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71Ar7WW01HL._SL1500_-678x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231512 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71Ar7WW01HL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg" alt="Halle Butler, Banal Nightmare" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71Ar7WW01HL._SL1500_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71Ar7WW01HL._SL1500_-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71Ar7WW01HL._SL1500_-768x1160.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71Ar7WW01HL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71Ar7WW01HL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/71Ar7WW01HL._SL1500_.jpg 993w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Halle Butler, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593730355" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Banal Nightmare</em></a><br />
Random House, July 16</strong></h5>
<p>Bulter (<a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780143133605" class="external" target="_blank"><em>The New Me</em></a>) is always biting and dark, but fun (in a depressing way). In her new novel, Moddie moves back to the Midwest after breaking up with her miserable long-term boyfriend, throwing herself at the mercy of her old friends and their lackluster lives. Everyone is unhappy, marriages are falling apart, emails are passive aggressive, and even a mysterious East Coast artist at the local university can’t jolt anyone awake. Another example of Bulter’s expert ease at creating unlikeable characters and satirizing the millennial generation. <em>–Emily Firetog, Deputy Editor</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="238914" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/fog-car-eugene-lim/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/fog-car-eugene-lim.jpeg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="fog &#038; car eugene lim" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/fog-car-eugene-lim-200x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/fog-car-eugene-lim.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-238914 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/fog-car-eugene-lim-200x300.jpeg" alt="Eugene Lim, Fog &amp; Car " width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/fog-car-eugene-lim-200x300.jpeg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/fog-car-eugene-lim-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/fog-car-eugene-lim-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/fog-car-eugene-lim.jpeg 667w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: right;"><strong>Eugene Lim, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781566896931" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Fog &amp; Car</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>Coffee House Press, July 16</strong></h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As previously recommended:</em></a> Eugene Lim’s debut comes back into print, thanks to the fine folks at Coffee House Press! Fans of <em>Dear Cyborgs</em> and <em>Search History</em> will be delighted to see the genesis of Lim’s searching and curious style, in a novel that follows a couple after their separation who can’t help continue to haunt each other’s lives through strange and surreal occurrences, rendered in strange and surreal prose. <em>–DB</em><strong> </strong></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="238915" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/brad-watson-there-is-happiness/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Brad-Watson-There-is-Happiness-.jpeg" data-orig-size="669,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Brad Watson, There is Happiness" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Brad-Watson-There-is-Happiness--201x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Brad-Watson-There-is-Happiness-.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-238915 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Brad-Watson-There-is-Happiness--201x300.jpeg" alt="Brad Watson, There is Happiness" width="201" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Brad-Watson-There-is-Happiness--201x300.jpeg 201w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Brad-Watson-There-is-Happiness--40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Brad-Watson-There-is-Happiness--33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Brad-Watson-There-is-Happiness-.jpeg 669w" sizes="(max-width: 201px) 100vw, 201px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Brad Watson, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781324076421" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">There is Happiness</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>W.W. Norton, July 16</strong></h5>
<p>The wonderful Southern writer Brad Watson—funny, strange, and criminally underread, in my opinion, despite his accolades, but <a href="https://lithub.com/in-sunshine-and-in-shadow-remembering-the-quiet-genius-of-brad-watson/">beloved by those in the know</a>—died in 2020 at only 64. What a joy to discover there is more work to come from him, in the form of this posthumous collection of stories, including some that were previously unpublished. It’s introduced by Joy Williams, which should give you a sense, but even better to take this as an opportunity to read (or re-read) Watson’s whole oeuvre. <em>–ET</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231513" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/81yuwsrm2al-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81yuwSrM2AL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="987,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Lev Grossman, The Bright Sword" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81yuwSrM2AL._SL1500_-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81yuwSrM2AL._SL1500_-674x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231513 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81yuwSrM2AL._SL1500_-197x300.jpg" alt="Lev Grossman, The Bright Sword" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81yuwSrM2AL._SL1500_-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81yuwSrM2AL._SL1500_-674x1024.jpg 674w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81yuwSrM2AL._SL1500_-768x1167.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81yuwSrM2AL._SL1500_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81yuwSrM2AL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81yuwSrM2AL._SL1500_.jpg 987w" sizes="(max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></h5>
<h5 class="Body" style="text-align: right;"><b>Lev Grossman, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780735224049" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><i>The Bright Sword</i></a><br />
Viking, July 16</b></h5>
<p class="Body"><a href="https://lithub.com/18-new-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As previously recommended:</em></a> I mentioned the summer of Arthur earlier—here’s the big one, the tentpole, the book I’ve been waiting for nearly a decade: Lev Grossman’s Arthurian epic, clocking in at nearly 700 pages and absolutely worth lugging to the beach/the mountains/the park/wherever else you might be vacationing. I’m happy to report that this book is not only one of the best of the year, but it’s one of the best Arthurian novels ever. Stand it up against <i>The Once and Future King</i> or <i>The Mists of Avalon</i> and I’d be willing to bet that it will come away the victor—it’s <i>that good</i>.</p>
<p class="Body">Probably because it doesn’t bother with trying to tell the stories you’ve already heard a thousand times, but instead it picks up with a young knight on his way to Camelot to join the Round Table, only to find that nearly everybody is dead or gone and the only knights left are a rag-tag bunch from the edges of the well-known tales. Grossman uses these characters to show different angles Arthur’s court, to bring more diverse voices into the legend of the Round Table, and to craft a story that genuinely answers the question of why Arthurian legend continues to speak to us across the centuries. It’s this generation’s great Arthur story and a rich reminder of the power we have—maybe even the responsibility—to reshape legend. <em>–DB</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="238916" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/c-michelle-lindley-the-nude/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/C.-Michelle-Lindley-The-Nude.jpeg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="C. Michelle Lindley, The Nude" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/C.-Michelle-Lindley-The-Nude-199x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/C.-Michelle-Lindley-The-Nude.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-238916 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/C.-Michelle-Lindley-The-Nude-199x300.jpeg" alt="C. Michelle Lindley, The Nude" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/C.-Michelle-Lindley-The-Nude-199x300.jpeg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/C.-Michelle-Lindley-The-Nude-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/C.-Michelle-Lindley-The-Nude-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/C.-Michelle-Lindley-The-Nude.jpeg 662w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>C. Michelle Lindley, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668032954" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Nude</a><br />
</em>Atria Books, July 23</strong></h5>
<p>If there’s one thing that’s true throughout the Western literary canon, it’s that a trip in Greece is never going to be simple. This debut novel is set on a Greek island off the southern coast, where an art historian is seeking a rare sculpture: the nude. But the trip gets complicated quickly, and the disoriented historian is ensnared by the sensuous island and pulled in by an enthralling and subversive female artist, forcing her to grapple with her place in the art world. What trip to the Mediterranean would be complete without a sensual and provocative examination of your own role in global systems of capital and ownership? <em>–JF</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="238917" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/feh-shalom-auslander/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/feh-shalom-auslander.jpeg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="feh shalom auslander" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/feh-shalom-auslander-200x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/feh-shalom-auslander.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-238917 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/feh-shalom-auslander-200x300.jpeg" alt="feh shalom auslander" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/feh-shalom-auslander-200x300.jpeg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/feh-shalom-auslander-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/feh-shalom-auslander-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/feh-shalom-auslander.jpeg 667w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: right;"><strong>Shalom Auslander, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780735213265" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Feh: A Memoir</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>Riverhead, July 23</strong></h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As previously recommended:</em></a> Yiddish for “Yuck,” <em>Feh</em> tells the story of Auslander’s upbringing in Monsey, New York by a dysfunctional Orthodox Jewish family, and recounts “his attempt to exorcize the story he was raised with—before he inflicts it onto his children and/or possibly poisons the relationship of the one woman who loves him.” Featuring Phillip Seymour Hoffman, a Pulitzer-winning poet, Job, Author Schopenhauer, Wolf Blitzer, and the pastor of a now-defunct church in LA, the memoir promises to be as funny and heartfelt as his other books. <em>–Emily Firetog, Deputy Editor</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231515" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/91fow5xeeel-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91FoW5XEeeL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Sarah Manguso, Liars" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91FoW5XEeeL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91FoW5XEeeL._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231515 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91FoW5XEeeL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" alt="Sarah Manguso, Liars" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91FoW5XEeeL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91FoW5XEeeL._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91FoW5XEeeL._SL1500_-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91FoW5XEeeL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91FoW5XEeeL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/91FoW5XEeeL._SL1500_.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Sarah Manguso, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593241257" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Liars</em></a><br />
Random House, July 23</strong></h5>
<p>There’s rarely been such a plethora of divorce books in one season, but 2024 just keeps them coming. There’s been a marked uptick in the portrayal of marriage falling apart these past months, and it’s still not slowing: Leslie Jamison’s <em>Splinters</em>, Lyz Lorenz’s <em>This American Ex-Wife</em>, and Miranda July’s <em>All Fours</em> all center dissolution and renewal, looking back while trying to look forward, and ultimately: choosing oneself over the union. <em>Liars</em> joins the oeuvre: written in Manguso’s trademark short prose, it depicts the story of her marriage through every up and down, every small moment of connection, every mundanity. Manguso’s marriage can read as both rife with red flags, and in another sense, a totally normal marriage, packed with disappointments and joys in every direction. When the end does come, it manages to still be a surprise to Manguso, even through every sign and symptom of disconnection and separation, reminding the reader marriage is largely a belief system. It’s only when someone stops believing that it all comes apart, but the faith can be tested only so many times. <em>–JH</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="238918" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/the-book-of-elsewhere-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/The-Book-of-Elsewhere-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="676,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="The Book of Elsewhere copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/The-Book-of-Elsewhere-copy-203x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/The-Book-of-Elsewhere-copy.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-238918 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/The-Book-of-Elsewhere-copy-203x300.jpg" alt="" width="203" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/The-Book-of-Elsewhere-copy-203x300.jpg 203w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/The-Book-of-Elsewhere-copy-41x60.jpg 41w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/The-Book-of-Elsewhere-copy-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/The-Book-of-Elsewhere-copy.jpg 676w" sizes="(max-width: 203px) 100vw, 203px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: right;"><strong>Keanu Reeves &amp; China Mieville, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593446591" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Book of Elsewhere</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Del Rey, July 23</strong></h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/our-21-most-anticipated-sci-fi-fantasy-and-horror-books-for-the-rest-of-2024/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As previously recommended:</em></a> I still can&#8217;t believe this book exists. Miéville and Reeves turn out to be a great match, and I for one will take new Miéville fiction however I can get it. Come for the action set-pieces and techno-thriller plotting but stay for the immortal pig(!) and the stirring digressions on ethics, morality, and humanity. It&#8217;s nothing like you could possibly expect, so don&#8217;t even bother: just dive in.<em>–DB</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="238933" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/autocracy-inc/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Autocracy-Inc.jpeg" data-orig-size="671,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Autocracy, Inc." data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Autocracy-Inc-201x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Autocracy-Inc.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-238933 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Autocracy-Inc-201x300.jpeg" alt="Autocracy, Inc." width="201" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Autocracy-Inc-201x300.jpeg 201w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Autocracy-Inc-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Autocracy-Inc-34x50.jpeg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Autocracy-Inc.jpeg 671w" sizes="(max-width: 201px) 100vw, 201px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Anne Applebaum, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780385549936" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Autocracy, Inc.</a><br />
</em>Doubleday, July 23</strong></h5>
<p>Between autocracy and climate change we really are in the middle of a long, slow boil (we would be the frogs in this metaphor, I’m afraid to say). Speaking to the former, Anne Applebaum’s latest is a warning as to just how close we are to a subtler, more pervasive form of autocratic power, more fluid, easier to globalize. Shining a light as it does on the transnational networks—technological, financial—that abet the consolidation of power in the hands of the few, to the detriment of everyone else, <em>Autocracy Inc.</em> is an important read (even if you don’t agree with Applebaum about who, exactly, the villains are). <em>–JD</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="239392" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/willy-vlautin-the-horse/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Willy-Vlautin-The-Horse-.jpeg" data-orig-size="663,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Willy Vlautin, The Horse" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Willy-Vlautin-The-Horse--199x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Willy-Vlautin-The-Horse-.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-239392 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Willy-Vlautin-The-Horse--199x300.jpeg" alt="Willy Vlautin, The Horse " width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Willy-Vlautin-The-Horse--199x300.jpeg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Willy-Vlautin-The-Horse--40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Willy-Vlautin-The-Horse--33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Willy-Vlautin-The-Horse-.jpeg 663w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: right;"><strong>Willy Vlautin, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063346574" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Horse</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>Harper, July 30</strong></h5>
<p>The seventh novel from award-winning, horse-loving, Oregon-based writer Vlautin (<em>Lean on Pete</em>) is the story of a grizzled former musician, living in tortured isolation in the high desert of central Nevada, whose descent into madness and despair is interrupted by the arrival on his doorstep of a blind (and possibly phantom) horse. Billed as a “poignant meditation on addiction, heartbreak, and the reality of life on the road in smalltime bands,” <em>The Horse</em> sounds like a beautiful addition to Vlautin’s stable of books about, as Ann Patchett once put it, “people overlooked by society and overlooked by literature.” <em>–DS</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="237453" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/18-new-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/91fcibipjcl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91FCIbiPjCL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="jessica anthony the most" data-image-description="&lt;p&gt;jessica anthony the most&lt;/p&gt;
" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91FCIbiPjCL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91FCIbiPjCL._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-237453 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91FCIbiPjCL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg" alt="jessica anthony the most" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91FCIbiPjCL._SL1500_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91FCIbiPjCL._SL1500_-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91FCIbiPjCL._SL1500_-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91FCIbiPjCL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91FCIbiPjCL._SL1500_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/91FCIbiPjCL._SL1500_.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Jessica Anthony, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780316576376" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Most</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Little, Brown, July 30</strong></h5>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/18-new-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>As previously recommended:</em></a> Another short novel that takes place in a single day—this may be the perfect summer form. In it, a housewife gets into the pool of her apartment complex—it&#8217;s a freakishly warm November day in 1957—and refuses to come out. The book slips between her perspective and that of her bewildered husband, neither of whom, it soon becomes clear, has been being completely (or even slightly) honest with the other. The whole thing has the extraordinarily pleasurable texture of gossip, wrapped up in the slightly eerie texture of a Cheever story. I read it straight through. <em>–ET</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="239391" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/ilan-pappe-lobbying-for-zionism-on-both-sides-of-the-atlantic/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Ilan-Pappe-Lobbying-for-Zionism-on-Both-Sides-of-the-Atlantic-.jpeg" data-orig-size="654,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Ilan Pappé, Lobbying for Zionism on Both Sides of the Atlantic" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Ilan-Pappe-Lobbying-for-Zionism-on-Both-Sides-of-the-Atlantic--196x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Ilan-Pappe-Lobbying-for-Zionism-on-Both-Sides-of-the-Atlantic-.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-239391 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Ilan-Pappe-Lobbying-for-Zionism-on-Both-Sides-of-the-Atlantic--196x300.jpeg" alt="Ilan Pappé, Lobbying for Zionism on Both Sides of the Atlantic " width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Ilan-Pappe-Lobbying-for-Zionism-on-Both-Sides-of-the-Atlantic--196x300.jpeg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Ilan-Pappe-Lobbying-for-Zionism-on-Both-Sides-of-the-Atlantic--39x60.jpeg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Ilan-Pappe-Lobbying-for-Zionism-on-Both-Sides-of-the-Atlantic--33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Ilan-Pappe-Lobbying-for-Zionism-on-Both-Sides-of-the-Atlantic-.jpeg 654w" sizes="(max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" /></p>
<h5 style="text-align: right;"><strong>Ilan Pappé, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780861544028" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Lobbying for Zionism on Both Sides of the Atlantic</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>One World, July 30</strong></h5>
<p>The latest work from esteemed Israeli historian and social activist Ilan Pappé (<em>The Ethnic Cleansing of Palestine</em>)<em> </em>is an examination of how the Israel lobby has, for over a century, “convinced British and American policymakers to condone Israel’s flagrant breaches of international law, grant Israel unprecedented military aid and deny Palestinians rights.” As Israel’s brutal assault on Gaza enters its ninth month, as AIPAC-funded American politicians on both sides of the aisle continue to excuse a genocide, as the Israel lobby perverts our elections with more vigor than ever, this book could not be more timely or essential. <em>–DS</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231516" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/81bq4yr6gzl-_sl1500_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81bq4YR6GzL._SL1500_.jpg" data-orig-size="1007,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Dinaw Mengestu, Someone Like Us" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81bq4YR6GzL._SL1500_-201x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81bq4YR6GzL._SL1500_-687x1024.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231516 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81bq4YR6GzL._SL1500_-201x300.jpg" alt="Dinaw Mengestu, Someone Like Us" width="201" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81bq4YR6GzL._SL1500_-201x300.jpg 201w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81bq4YR6GzL._SL1500_-687x1024.jpg 687w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81bq4YR6GzL._SL1500_-768x1144.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81bq4YR6GzL._SL1500_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81bq4YR6GzL._SL1500_-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/81bq4YR6GzL._SL1500_.jpg 1007w" sizes="(max-width: 201px) 100vw, 201px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Dinaw Mengestu, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780385350006" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Someone Like Us</em></a><br />
Knopf, July 30</strong></h5>
<p>The fourth novel from the multi-award winning Mengestu is the story of Mamush, an Ethiopian American former journalist who returns from Paris (where his marriage is fraying) to the close-knit immigrant community of Washington, DC, that defined his childhood. When Samuel, the beloved-but-troubled family friend who turned out to be Mamush’s biological father, dies suddenly, Mamush (with the ghost of Samuel in his ear) sets out on a journey across America in an effort to understand both the mysteries of Samuel’s life, and the buried secrets of his own early childhood. I’ve been hearing wonderful things about this one for months now and can’t wait to check it out. <em>–DS</em></p>
<h5><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231623" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024/attachment/9780593802564/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9780593802564.jpg" data-orig-size="307,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Siân Hughes, Pearl" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9780593802564-205x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9780593802564.jpg" class="size-medium wp-image-231623 alignright" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9780593802564-205x300.jpg" alt="Siân Hughes, Pearl" width="205" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9780593802564-205x300.jpg 205w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9780593802564-41x60.jpg 41w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9780593802564-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/9780593802564.jpg 307w" sizes="(max-width: 205px) 100vw, 205px" /></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: right;"><strong>Siân Hughes, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593802564" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Pearl</a><br />
</em>Knopf, July 30</strong></h5>
<p>Hughes&#8217; gorgeous novel was long-listed for The Booker Prize last year, and is going into a new, Knopf printing this year. The book follows Marianne, who is fixated on her mother who went missing when Marianne was just eight. Marianne discovers &#8220;Pearl,&#8221; a poem from the Middle Ages preserved in a manuscript alongside Gawain and the Green Knight. Marianne sees her grief and love reflected in the preserved, 14th-century lines, and attempts to illustrate it, drawing her closer to her pain. She’s drawn as well to an abandoned chapel, where another discovery begins to erode her memories and assumptions. Hughes’ placid and deep novel chains sorrows to each other as the narrative unfurls, creating a delicate tether connecting moments of loss. <em>–JF</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="238947" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/bret-anthony-johnston-we-burn-daylight/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Bret-Anthony-Johnston-We-Burn-Daylight-.jpeg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Bret Anthony Johnston, We Burn Daylight" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Bret-Anthony-Johnston-We-Burn-Daylight--199x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Bret-Anthony-Johnston-We-Burn-Daylight-.jpeg" class="size-medium wp-image-238947 alignleft" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Bret-Anthony-Johnston-We-Burn-Daylight--199x300.jpeg" alt="Bret Anthony Johnston, We Burn Daylight" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Bret-Anthony-Johnston-We-Burn-Daylight--199x300.jpeg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Bret-Anthony-Johnston-We-Burn-Daylight--40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Bret-Anthony-Johnston-We-Burn-Daylight--33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Bret-Anthony-Johnston-We-Burn-Daylight-.jpeg 662w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h5 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Bret Anthony Johnston, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780399590122" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>We Burn Daylight</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Random House, July 30</strong></h5>
<p>That setting tells you straightaway what this one’s going to be about: the Branch Davidians, the Waco siege, and the ordinary lives caught up in a flash-point moment that will reverberate for a generation to come. We Burn Daylight uses the perspectives of two star-crossed lovers—the sheriff’s son and the unbelieving daughter of a cult member—to navigate the complexities of the showdown, for a moving and epic tale. I would expect no less from Johnston.<em>–MO</em></p>
										
										<div class="content-page-links"><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/2/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num prev-link"></span></a><span class="page-link-numbers"> <span class="post-page-numbers current" aria-current="page"><span class="page-link-num">1</span></span> <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/2/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num">2</span></a> <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/3/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num">3</span></a> <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/4/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num">4</span></a> <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/5/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num">5</span></a> <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/6/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num">6</span></a></span> <a href="?single=true">Full Page</a><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2024-part-two/2/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num next-link">&gt;&gt;</span></a></div>										
																		
										<div class="post_wrapper author">
											<div id="about_the_author">
												<div class="gravatar"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/emily-temple/"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/Emily-Temple_select_9612_NS1sm-100x100.jpg" width="100" height="100" alt="Emily Temple" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></a></div>
												<div class="description author withsidebar">
													<h6><a href="https://lithub.com/author/emily-temple/">Emily Temple</a></h6>
													Emily Temple is the managing editor at Lit Hub. Her first novel, <em>The Lightness</em>, was published by William Morrow/HarperCollins in June 2020. <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/317/9780062905338" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="external" target="_blank">You can buy it here.</a>																										<div class="website">
						    							<i class="fa fa-link"></i>
							    						<a href="https://www.emilytemple.net/" target="_blank" class="external">https://www.emilytemple.net/</a>
							    					</div>
